<tr valign=baseline><td nowrap width="20%" align=right><b>Average Fun Rating: </b></td><td colspan=4 width="80%" align=left><a style="text-decoration: none; color:black" href="rate/showrate.pl?gid=232" target="showrate232"><img src="stars/6stars.png" height=18 width=201 border=0 alt="[ 6 stars - Click for comments ]">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>6.4</b>/10&nbsp;&nbsp;</a>(<a href="rate/showrate.pl?gid=232" target="showrate232">24 ratings/18 comments</a>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[ <a href="rate/login.pl?gid=232" target="do_a_rating">Add Your Rating!</a> ]
</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Manufacturer: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><span title="Click here to perform a search for all pinball games manufactured by 'Williams'"><a href="search.pl?searchtype=advanced&amp;mfgid=351">Williams Electronics, Incorporated (1967-1985) <i>[Trade Name: Williams</i>]</a></span></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Date Of Manufacture: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>April 09, 1975</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Model Number: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>456</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Type: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>Electro-mechanical (EM)&nbsp;<a href="showhelp.pl?item=type&amp;highlight=EM#EM" title="Show Type Classifications" target="help"><img alt="[?]" style="cursor: help;" src="/graphic/question.gif" border=0></a></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Production: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>2,900 units &nbsp;&nbsp;<font size="-1">(<i>confirmed</i>)</font></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" align="right" valign=baseline><b>Serial Number Database:</b></td><td colspan=4 align="left" valign=baseline><a href="redirect.pl?http://www.ipsnd.net/View.aspx?id=232">View at <I>The Internet Pinball Serial Number Database</I> (IPSND.net)</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<font size="-1"><I>(External site)</i></font></td></tr><tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Theme: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>World Places - Landmarks</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Notable Features: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Flipper">Flippers</a> (2), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Pop_Bumper">Pop&nbsp;bumpers</a> (2), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Drop_Target">Drop&nbsp;targets</a> (3), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Kick-out_Hole">Kick-out&nbsp;hole</a> (1).</td></tr>
<tr><td width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Design by: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><span title="Click here to perform a search for all pinball games that 'Steve&nbsp;Kordek' was connected with."><a href="search.pl?searchtype=advanced&amp;ppl=Steve%20Kordek">Steve&nbsp;Kordek</a></span></td></tr>
<tr><td width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Art by: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><span title="Click here to perform a search for all pinball games that 'Christian&nbsp;Marche' was connected with."><a href="search.pl?searchtype=advanced&amp;ppl=Christian%20Marche">Christian&nbsp;Marche</a></span></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Notes: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>Game is convertible between <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Replay">replay</a> and <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Add-A-Ball">add-a-ball</a> operation.<br><br>The games pictured in this listing show two styles of <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Pop_Bumper">pop&nbsp;bumper</a> caps. Williams used either of these two styles in their games produced from May 1973 to January 1976. We expect that their flyer predicts the style that was used for the entire production run. Most likely, whenever the caps needed to be replaced, <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Operator">operators</a> used whichever style they had handy, as either one would fit on the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Pop_Bumper">pop&nbsp;bumper</a> bodies of the games Williams made during this period.<P></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" align=right valign=baseline><b>Photos in: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>
